## Why two versions

The public version builds audience trust, keeps you honest, and is what people actually want to see. Specific dollar figures and growth rates.

The internal version is for your decision-making. It includes:
- Cost detail (which would invite competitor copying, doesn't help anyone)
- Churn count by reason (which would identify specific clients if shared)
- W2-replacement-tracker (a personal financial number that doesn't belong on YouTube)
- Pipeline coverage (a leading indicator that's useful internally but creates wrong expectations externally)

## How to fill it

The Operations Agent automates ~90% of this from HubSpot, Stripe, Wave, and Smartlead. The fields it CAN'T auto-fill:
- "Said I'd: result" — qualitative, needs your judgment
- "Goals for next month" — your decision
- Loss reason breakdown — needs HubSpot data + your interpretation
- "Time allocation" — you log this in a simple weekly time-tracker (or estimate honestly at month-end)

## Cadence

- **By month-end:** Internal scoreboard complete. Used in monthly retro.
- **First business day of new month:** Public scoreboard generated. Used in YouTube episode + blog post.
- **Episode publishes by:** 7th of new month.

## What to do if a number is bad

Show it anyway. The whole point of the public scoreboard is that you don't get to hide on bad months.

If MRR dropped, that's the lead. Don't bury it. The audience that consumes this content is *more* interested in a $200 month than a $5,000 month — the former is rare in build-in-public content because most people quit instead of filming.
